==Old English==
===Etymology 1===
From Germanic ''*fūr-'', from Indo-European ''*peh₂u̯r̥, *pūr''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[fiur]], Old Saxon [[fiur]] (Dutch [[vuur]]), Old High German [[fiur]] (German [[Feuer]]), Old Norse [[furr|fúrr]], [[fyrr|fýrr]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[πυρ|πῦρ]].

====Pronunciation====
{{IPA|/fy:r/}}

====Noun====
{{Latinx|'''fȳr'''}} {{n}} (plural {{Latinx|'''[[fyre|fȳra]]'''}} or {{Latinx|'''[[fyre|fȳre]]'''}})
# [[fire]]
#:''Ðæs fyres gecynd is hat and drie.''  Fire’s nature is hot and dry. (''Screadunga'')

